suiban is the inference & orchestration core of the bonsai stack. It runs the
PrismML Bonsai model family on a local PrismML llama.cpp fork. The credits below
cover the models, the fork, the vendored KV-cache patchset and the third-party
libraries suiban depends on.

================================================================================
Models and the inference fork
================================================================================

PrismML Bonsai models
  The Bonsai 27B / 8B / 4B / 1.7B model family (ternary `Q2_0` and 1-bit `Q1_0`
  GGUF builds), published by PrismML on Hugging Face under `prism-ml/*`
  (e.g. prism-ml/Ternary-Bonsai-27B-gguf, prism-ml/Bonsai-27B-gguf). Weights are
  downloaded at install time; they are not redistributed in this repository and
  carry their own upstream model license.

PrismML llama.cpp fork
  Inference is performed by prebuilt binaries of the PrismML llama.cpp fork,
  `PrismML-Eng/llama.cpp` (branch `prism`), pinned to release
  `prism-b9596-9fcaed7`. The fork is downloaded at install time and is not
  redistributed here.

llama.cpp / ggml (MIT)
  The fork, and suiban's vendored patchset, build on llama.cpp and ggml.
  Copyright (c) 2023-2026 The ggml authors. Licensed under the MIT License.
  https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp

================================================================================
TurboQuant KV-cache patchset (suiban/vendor/)
================================================================================

TurboQuant algorithm
  A. Zandieh, M. Daliri, M. Hagemann, S. Voinea, I. Han,
  "TurboQuant: Online Vector Quantization with Near-optimal Distortion Rate,"
  arXiv:2504.19874. https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.19874
  suiban's `TQ4_0` / `TQ3_0` GGML types implement this algorithm's MSE variant.

TQ3_0 CPU reference port (MIT)
  suiban's `TQ3_0` CPU kernels are ported from the MIT-licensed branch
  `Aaryan-Kapoor/llama.cpp`, branch `turboquant-tq3_0`, commit
  1fb1fb3ab6b3e5c3776a362d7ac7f5985328d71b.
  Copyright (c) Aaryan Kapoor. Licensed under the MIT License.
  The quantization pipeline, the 8-level codebook constants, the 3-bit packing
  scheme and the test tolerance come from that branch. `TQ4_0` is an original
  extension of the same pattern to 16 levels. See vendor/README.md and
  docs/turboquant.md for the full patch inventory and divergences.

llama.cpp community discussion
  The randomized-Hadamard-transform substitution for the paper's Gaussian
  rotation follows the consensus in the llama.cpp community discussion
  ggml-org/llama.cpp#20969
  (https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/discussions/20969). Cited for its
  ideas and reported numbers; no code from it is used.

Community CUDA gist (no license, no code used)
  A community CUDA gist by Jim Sullivan (veritatisquaesitoressumus) carries NO
  license. None of its code is used in this repository. It is cited in
  vendor/README.md and docs/turboquant.md for its published measurement numbers
  and integration ideas only; suiban's CUDA kernels (patches 0005-0007) are
  clean-room work derived from the CPU reference semantics and mainline
  quantized-KV CUDA idioms.

================================================================================
Skills and memory
================================================================================

agentskills.io
  suiban's skill format (SKILL.md frontmatter with `name` / `description`) is
  compatible with the agentskills.io convention. https://agentskills.io

Skill-format interoperability: openclaw and Hermes (MIT, no code copied)
  suiban can import agentskills.io `SKILL.md` directory skills from other
  ecosystems, and its own skills export back the same way (the format is
  portable both directions). Two such ecosystems are supported by name:
    - openclaw: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw (MIT)
    - Hermes (hermes-agent): https://github.com/nousresearch/hermes-agent (MIT)
  Only their `SKILL.md` skills are read, through the shared agentskills.io
  format; NO source code from either project is used or redistributed here.

Hermes memory architecture (design inspiration, no code)
  suiban's layered, on-demand memory design (cheap always-available identity /
  state layers plus retrieval that is fetched by tool call rather than always
  prepended) is inspired by the Hermes memory architecture. The inspiration is
  conceptual only: the four-layer split and the visible, tool-driven recall
  approach were informed by it, while suiban's storage (plain files + SQLite
  FTS5), write-enforcement rules and implementation are its own. No code was
  borrowed. See docs/memory.md.

